You are working in a Next.js 16 App Router codebase with React 19 and Tailwind v4.

Follow these standards unless the user explicitly asks otherwise:

## General
- Prefer existing patterns in the repo over inventing new ones
- Prefer small, composable components over large multi-purpose ones
- Keep code production-ready and maintainable
- Avoid unnecessary dependencies — framer-motion, gsap, lucide-react, and vaul are already available
- Keep logic readable and straightforward

## TypeScript
- Prefer explicit, narrow types
- Avoid `any` unless absolutely necessary
- Keep props minimal and well named
- Prefer derived state over duplicated state

## Next.js App Router
- Components are Server Components by default — only add `"use client"` when the component needs browser APIs, hooks, or event handlers
- Use the existing `ClientOnly` wrapper for components that must avoid SSR
- Path alias is `@/*` mapping to `web/*`

## React / UI structure
- Use semantic HTML where possible
- Prefer `<button>` for actions and `<a>` / `next/link` for navigation
- Avoid div-heavy markup when a more semantic element exists
- Keep JSX nesting under control
- Extract repeated UI into reusable components when it improves clarity

## Styling
- Tailwind v4 is configured via CSS — theme tokens live in `globals.css` as CSS variables
- Reuse existing tokens: `--background`, `--foreground`, `--primary`, `--gold`, `--card`, etc.
- Reuse existing utility classes: `.glass-card`, `.cta-btn`, `.btn-secondary`, `.parallax-bg`
- Keep spacing, typography, and colours consistent with the existing design system
- Avoid magic numbers unless already established
- Prefer responsive layouts by default

## Accessibility
- Ensure keyboard operability for interactive elements
- Ensure visible focus states are preserved
- Use labels, descriptions, and headings properly
- Prefer native semantics over unnecessary ARIA
- Do not add ARIA that duplicates native behaviour
- Preserve existing patterns: `<SkipNavLink />`, `<ScrollProgress />`

## UX quality
- Consider loading, empty, error, and success states
- Ensure important actions are visually clear
- Preserve clear hierarchy and scannability
- Reduce unnecessary friction in forms and flows
- Respect `prefers-reduced-motion` when using framer-motion or gsap animations

## Output behaviour
When making changes:
- Briefly explain the approach
- Mention any important tradeoffs
- Call out accessibility or responsive considerations when relevant
